Registration of town or village green: statement by owner
In the Commons Act 2006, after section 15 (registration of greens) insert
Registration of greens: statement by owner
Where the owner of any land in England to which this Part applies
deposits with the commons registration authority a statement in the
prescribed form, the statement is to be regarded, for the purposes of
section 15, as bringing to an end any period during which persons have
indulged as of right in lawful sports and pastimes on the land to which
the statement relates.
Subsection (1) does not prevent a new period commencing.
A statement under subsection (1) must be accompanied by a map in the
prescribed form identifying the land to which the statement relates.
An owner of land may deposit more than one statement under
subsection (1) in respect of the same land.
If more than one statement is deposited in respect of the same land, a
later statement (whether or not made by the same person) may refer to
the map which accompanied an earlier statement and that map is to be
treated, for the purposes of this section, as also accompanying the later
statement.
Where a statement is deposited under subsection (1), the commons
registration authority must take the prescribed steps in relation to the
statement and accompanying map and do so in the prescribed manner
and within the prescribed period (if any).
Regulations may make provision
for a statement required for the purposes of this section to be
combined with a statement or declaration required for the
purposes of section 31(6) of the Highways Act 1980;
for the requirement in subsection (3) to be satisfied by the
statement referring to a map previously deposited under
section 31(6) of the Highways Act 1980;
as to the fees payable in relation to the depositing of a statement
under subsection (1) (including provision for a fee payable
under the regulations to be determined by the commons
registration authority);
as to when a statement under subsection (1) is to be regarded as
having been deposited with the commons registration
authority.
An agreement under section 4(3) of this Act or section 2(2) of the
Commons Registration Act 1965 which would have the effect of
requiring an owner of land to deposit a statement under subsection (1)
with a registration authority in Wales is to be disregarded for the
purposes of this section.

town or village green ceases to apply if an event specified in the first
column of the Table set out in Schedule 1A has occurred in relation to
the land (\xd2 a trigger event\xd3 ).
Where the right under section 15(1) has ceased to apply because of the
occurrence of a trigger event, it becomes exercisable again only if an
event specified in the corresponding entry in the second column of the
Table occurs in relation to the land (\xd2 a terminating event\xd3 ).
The Secretary of State may by order make provision as to when a
trigger or a terminating event is to be treated as having occurred for the
purposes of this section.
The Secretary of State may by order provide that subsection (1) does not
apply in circumstances specified in the order.
The Secretary of State may by order amend Schedule 1A so as to
specify additional trigger or terminating events;
amend or omit any of the trigger or terminating events for the
time being specified in the Schedule.

(5)(a) must be an event related to the development (whether past,
present or future) of the land.

subsection (5)(a) specifying an additional trigger or terminating event
includes provision for this section to apply where such an event has
occurred before the order is made or before it comes into force and as
to its application in such a case.

15 is made within the period of two years mentioned in section 15(3)(c),
any period during which an application to register land as a town or
village green may not be made by virtue of this section is to be
disregarded.\xd3

The power in section 35(1) to give a direction in a case within section

response to a qualifying request if no application for a consent or
authorisation mentioned in section 33(1) or (2) has been made in

The power in section 35(1) to give a direction in a case within section
35(2)(a)(ii) (business or commercial projects of prescribed description)
is exercisable only in response to a qualifying request made by one or
more of the following
a person who proposes to carry out any of the development to
which the request relates;
a person who has applied, or proposes to apply, for a consent or
authorisation mentioned in section 33(1) or (2) in relation to any
of that development;
a person who, if a direction under section 35(1) is given in
relation to that development, proposes to apply for an order
granting development consent for any of that development.
If the Secretary of State gives a direction under section 35(1) in relation
to development, the Secretary of State may
if an application for a consent or authorisation mentioned in
section 33(1) or (2) has been made in relation to the
development, direct the application to be treated as an
application for an order granting development consent;
if a person proposes to make an application for such a consent
or authorisation in relation to the development, direct the
proposed application to be treated as a proposed application for
development consent.
A direction under section 35(1), or subsection (3) of this section, may be
given so as to apply for specified purposes or generally.
A direction under subsection (3) may provide for specified provisions
of or made under this or any other Act
to have effect in relation to the application, or proposed
application, with any specified modifications, or
to be treated as having been complied with in relation to the
application or proposed application.
If the Secretary of State gives a direction under subsection (3), the
relevant authority must refer the application, or proposed application,
to the Secretary of State instead of dealing with it themselves.
If the Secretary of State is considering whether to give a direction under
subsection (3), the Secretary of State may direct the relevant authority
to take no further action in relation to the application, or proposed
application, until the Secretary of State has decided whether to give the
direction.
The Secretary of State may require an authority within subsection (9) to
provide any information required by the Secretary of State for the
purpose of enabling the Secretary of State to decide
whether to give a direction under section 35(1), and
the terms in which such a direction should be given.
An authority is within this subsection if an application for a consent or
authorisation mentioned in section 33(1) or (2) in relation to the
development has been, or may be, made to it.
If the Secretary of State decides to give a direction under section 35(1),
the Secretary of State must give reasons for the decision.

ParaLine.String: Section
Planning applications made to Secretary of State: further amendments
Town and Country Planning Act 1990
The Town and Country Planning Act 1990 is amended as follows.
In section 2A (Mayor of London: applications of strategic importance) after
subsection (1A) insert
Where this section applies to an application for planning permission
made to the Secretary of State under section 62A, the Mayor of
London may direct
that the application is to be treated as having been made to
the local planning authority (and not to the Secretary of State
under section 62A), and
that the Mayor of London is to be the local planning authority
for the purposes of determining the application.\xd3
In consequence
in section 2A(2) after \xd2 (1)\xd3 insert \xd2 or (1B)\xd3 ,
in section 2B(8)(a) after \xd2 2A(1)\xd3 insert \xd2 or (1B)\xd3 , and
in section 2C(1) after \xd2 to whom the original application was made\xd3
insert \xd2 or to whom the original application would have been made
had it not been made to the Secretary of State under section 62A\xd3 .
In section 58(1)(b) (planning permission may be granted on application to
local planning authority) after \xd2 on application to the authority\xd3 insert \xd2 (or,
in the cases provided in this Part, on application to the Secretary of State)\xd3 .
In section 59(2)(b) (development order may provide for planning permission
to be granted on application to local planning authority) after \xd2 on
application to the authority\xd3 insert \xd2 (or, in the cases provided in the
following provisions, on application to the Secretary of State)\xd3 .
After section 76B insert
Provisions applying to applications made under section 62A
Sections 62(3) and (4), 65(5), 70 to 70C, 72(1) and (5) and 73A apply,
with any necessary modifications, to an application for planning
permission made to the Secretary of State under section 62A as they
apply to an application for planning permission which is to be
determined by the local planning authority.
Any requirements imposed by a development order by virtue of
section 62, 65 or 71 may be applied by a development order, with or
without modifications, to an application for planning permission
made to the Secretary of State under section 62A.
Where an application is made to the Secretary of State under section
62A(3) instead of to the authority to whom it would otherwise have
been made, a development order may apply, with or without
modifications, to the application any enactment that relates to
applications of that kind when made to that authority.
Deciding applications made under section 62A
An application made to the Secretary of State under section 62A (\xd2 a
direct application\xd3 ) is to be determined by a person appointed by the
Secretary of State for the purpose instead of by the Secretary of State,
subject to section 76E.
Where a person has been appointed under subsection (1) or this
subsection to determine a direct application then, at any time before
the person has determined the application, the Secretary of State
may
revoke the person\xd5 s appointment; and
appoint another person to determine the application instead.
A person appointed under this section to determine an application
for planning permission made to the Secretary of State under section
62A has the same powers and duties that the Secretary of State has
under section 76C.
Where a direct application is determined by a person appointed
under this section, the person\xd5 s decision is to be treated as that of the
Secretary of State.
Except as provided by Part 12, the validity of that decision is not to
be questioned in any proceedings whatsoever.
It is not a ground of application to the High Court under section 288
that a direct application ought to have been determined by the
Secretary of State and not by a person appointed under this section
unless the applicant challenges the person\xd5 s power to determine the
direct application before the person\xd5 s decision on the direct
application is given.
Where any enactment (other than this section and section 319A)
refers (or is to be read as referring) to the Secretary of State in
a context relating to or capable of relating to an application
made under section 62A (otherwise than by referring to the
application having been made to the Secretary of State), or
refers (or is to be read as referring) to anything (other than the
making of the application) done or authorised or required to
be done by, to or before the Secretary of State in connection
with any such application,
then, so far as the context permits, the enactment is to be read, in
relation to an application determined or to be determined by a
person appointed under this section, as if the reference to the
Secretary of State were or included a reference to that person.
Applications under section 62A: determination by Secretary of State
The Secretary of State may direct that an application made to the
Secretary of State under section 62A (\xd2 a direct application\xd3 ) is to be
determined by the Secretary of State instead of by a person
appointed under section 76D.
Where a direction is given under subsection (1), the Secretary of State
must serve a copy of the direction on
the person, if any, appointed under section 76D to determine
the application concerned,
the applicant, and
the local planning authority.
Where a direct application is to be determined by the Secretary of
State in consequence of a direction under subsection (1)
in determining the application, the Secretary of State may
take into account any report made to the Secretary of State by
any person previously appointed to determine the
application, and
subject to that, the provisions of the planning Acts which are
relevant to the application apply to it as if section 76D had
never applied to it.
The Secretary of State may by a further direction revoke a direction
under subsection (1) at any time before the determination of the
direct application concerned.
Where a direction is given under subsection (4), the Secretary of State
must serve a copy of the direction on
the person, if any, previously appointed under section 76D to
determine the application concerned,
the applicant, and
the local planning authority.
Where a direction is given under subsection (4) in relation to a direct
application
anything done by or on behalf of the Secretary of State in
connection with the application which might have been done
by a person appointed under section 76D to determine the
application is, unless the person appointed under section 76D
to determine the application directs otherwise, to be treated
as having been done by that person, and
subject to that, section 76D applies to the application as if no
direction under subsection (1) had been given in relation to
the application.\xd3
In section 70A(2) (power to decline to determine planning application where
Secretary of State has refused similar application in previous two years) after
\xd2 has refused a similar application\xd3 insert \xd2 made to the Secretary of State
under section 62A or\xd3 .
In section 70B(3) (power to decline to determine planning application where
Secretary of State currently considering similar application) after \xd2 in
pursuance of section\xd3 insert \xd2 62A,\xd3 .
In section 78(2) (right to appeal where local planning authority has taken
none of the listed steps in relation to an application) after \xd2 made such an
application\xd3 insert \xd2 to the local planning authority\xd3 .
In section 284(3) (actions which may be questioned in legal proceedings only
so far as provided by Part 12 of the 1990 Act) before paragraph (za) insert
any decision on an application made to the Secretary of State
under section 62A;\xd3 .
In section 303 (fees for planning applications etc) as substituted by section
199 of the Planning Act 2008, after subsection (1) insert
The Secretary of State may by regulations make provision for the
payment of a fee to the Secretary of State in respect of
any application made to the Secretary of State under section
the giving of advice about applying under section 62A for
any permission, approval or consent or for anything else for
which an application may be made under that section.\xd3
In section 319A(7) (proceedings for which Secretary of State must determine
the procedure) before paragraph (a) insert
an application made to the Secretary of State under section

ParaLine.String: Section
Periodic review of mineral planning permissions
Schedule 14 to the Environment Act 1995 (periodic review of mineral
planning permissions) is amended as follows.
Before paragraph 1 insert
\xd2 Power to carry out periodic reviews
The mineral planning authority for an area in England may, in
accordance with the provisions of this Schedule, cause one or
more periodic reviews to be carried out of the mineral permissions
relating to a mining site.\xd3
In paragraph 1 (duty to carry out periodic reviews), after \xd2 The mineral
planning authority\xd3 insert \xd2 for an area in Wales\xd3 .
In paragraph 2(1) (interpretation), for the definition of \xd2 first review date\xd3
substitute
\xd2 \xd2 first review date\xd3
in relation to a mineral planning authority for an area
in England, has the meaning given by paragraph 2A
below, and
in relation to a mineral planning authority for an area
in Wales, has the meaning given by paragraph 2B
below;\xd3 .
After paragraph 2 insert
\xd2 The first review date: mineral planning authorities in England
In the application of this Schedule in relation to a mineral planning
authority for an area in England, \xd2 first review date\xd3 means the
date set by the authority in accordance with sub-paragraph (2)
below as the first review date for the purposes of the first periodic
review of the mineral permissions relating to a mining site.
That date may not be earlier than the relevant date found under
paragraph 3 below in relation to the site.
This paragraph is subject to paragraphs 3A and 5 below (power to
specify different relevant date, and postponement of first review
date).
The first review date: mineral planning authorities in Wales
In the application of this Schedule in relation to a mineral planning
authority for an area in Wales, \xd2 first review date\xd3 in relation to a
mining site means the relevant date found under paragraph 3
below in relation to the site.
This paragraph is subject to paragraphs 3A and 5 below (power to
specify different relevant date, and postponement of first review
date).\xd3
Paragraph 3 (the first review date) is amended as follows.
Before sub-paragraph (1) insert
This paragraph has effect for the purposes of paragraphs 2A and
2B above.\xd3
For \xd2 first review date\xd3 in each place substitute \xd2 relevant date\xd3 .
For the italic heading immediately before that paragraph substitute \xd2 The
relevant date for the purposes of a first periodic review\xd3 .
In paragraph 3A (power to specify a first review date by order), for \xd2 first
review date\xd3 in each place substitute \xd2 relevant date\xd3 .
Paragraph 4 (service of notice of first periodic review) is amended as
follows.
Before sub-paragraph (1) insert
This paragraph applies
where a mineral planning authority for an area in England
determines that it will carry out a periodic review of the
mineral permissions relating to a mining site, and that
periodic review is the first periodic review of the
permissions relating to that site, and
in relation to the first periodic review by a mineral
planning authority for an area in Wales of the mineral
permissions relating to a mining site.\xd3
In sub-paragraph (1)
omit \xd2 of the mineral permissions relating to a mining site\xd3 , and
for \xd2 that site\xd3 substitute \xd2 the site to which the review relates\xd3 .
Paragraph 12 (second and subsequent periodic reviews) is amended as
follows.
Before sub-paragraph (1) insert
This paragraph applies
where a mineral planning authority for an area in England
determines that it will carry out a periodic review of the
mineral permissions relating to a mining site, and that
periodic review is the second or a subsequent periodic
review of the permissions relating to that site, and
in relation to the second or any subsequent periodic review
by a mineral planning authority for an area in Wales of the
mineral permissions relating to a mining site.
In the application of this paragraph in relation to a mineral
planning authority for an area in England \xd2 the review date\xd3 means
the date set by the authority as the review date for the purposes of
the periodic review.
That date may not be earlier than the relevant date found under
sub-paragraph (1) below in relation to the site.
In the application of this paragraph in relation to a mineral
planning authority for an area in Wales \xd2 the review date\xd3 means
the relevant date found under sub-paragraph (1) below in relation
to the site.\xd3
In sub-paragraph (1), for \xd2 \xd2 review date\xd3 \xd3 substitute \xd2 \xd2 relevant date\xd3 \xd3 .
In sub-paragraph (2)
omit the \xd2 and\xd3 at the end of paragraph (a), and
at the end of paragraph (b) insert \xd2 , and
paragraph 4(A1) were omitted.\xd3

Splitting can occur anywhere within the Part/Chapter/CrossHeading structure of the clauses, or between Schedules. A split will never occur within a Schedule. Typically the split is only required for long Bills (e.g. Fincance Bill) where there is a physical limit to the number of pages that can be stapled by the printer. Mekon\qs FDK plugin actually allows for multiple splits, however, this will never really be more than 2 volumes.

This element is used to create cross references to <Chapter\> elements within the Bill book. Upon concatenation they are converted into regular <Xref\> elements.

The <DummyXref\> element is used within House amendments to indicate where a cross reference would be required when it is introduced into the Bill text. It is not intended for use within Bill text only.
This element is used to create cross references to <Part\> elements within the Bill book. Upon concatenation they are converted into regular <Xref\> elements.

The pagefit process tries each
code block in order. If a block
fails to fit the content to a
single page, it discards that
block\xd5 s changes, and tries the
next one. This continues until
ther is a fit, or until the code
blocks are exhausted.
